      "tags": [
        "multi-agent",
        "emergence"
      ],
      "score": 0.95,
      "hebbian_credit": 10,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.ma.new3",
      "snippet": "A pre-registered experiment testing two predictions of coupled multi-agent systems: information-theoretic capacity regions and mean-field residual scaling laws. Results confirm the information gap law: best-informed agent absorbs all wealth in 4/5 scenarios. Target dispersion collapse observed: all experiments fail to reach noise-sustained dispersion regime, exhibiting step response and bistability."
    },
    {
      "id": "inject-or-navigate-token-efficient-retrieval-for-l",
      "name": "Inject or Navigate? Token-Efficient Retrieval for LLM Analysis of Legal Documents",
      "dir": "inject-or-navigate-token-efficient-retrieval-for-l/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.CL:2607.new",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:01.795180+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:01.795180+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "long context",
        "memory"
      ],
      "score": 0.95,
      "hebbian_credit": 10,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.cl.new2",
      "snippet": "Compares full-context injection vs structured retrieval for legal document analysis. Full-context injection achieves high recall but massive token consumption and long-context degradation. Structured retrieval matches injection on 16/18 queries with 17.3x fewer input tokens. Derives caching cost cross rule: caching injection is cost-effective only when corpus is smaller than 10x payload."
    },
    {
      "id": "llm-agents-for-deliberative-collaboration-under-pa",
      "name": "LLM Agents for Deliberative Collaboration Under Partial Observability",
      "dir": "llm-agents-for-deliberative-collaboration-under-pa/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.CL:2607.new",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:01.804864+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:01.804864+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "multi-agent",
        "self-reflection"
      ],
      "score": 0.95,
      "hebbian_credit": 10,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.cl.new3",
      "snippet": "Formalizes deliberative collaboration as a cooperative joint decision-making problem with partial and asymmetric observations, creating a benchmark for evaluation. Systematic evaluation shows that complex deliberative collaboration remains challenging even for frontier LLMs. Analysis reveals deliberation sometimes enables reflection and correction opportunities, outperforming centralized baselines."
    },
    {
      "id": "prompt-robustness-is-task-dependent-objective-vs-b",
      "name": "Prompt Robustness Is Task-Dependent: Objective vs Belief-Style Questions in LLM Evaluation",
      "dir": "prompt-robustness-is-task-dependent-objective-vs-b/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.CL:2607.new",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:01.827085+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:01.827085+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "long context"
      ],
      "score": 0.75,
      "hebbian_credit": 8,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.cl.new1",
      "snippet": "This paper studies prompt robustness across different question types in LLM evaluation. Model, dataset, prompt category, and their interactions significantly affect robustness. Long-context tasks may be constrained by context window limitations. Prompt variation effects differ across objective vs subjective question types and across models. Provides implications for robust long-context evaluation design."
    },
    {
      "id": "rethinking-query-optimization-for-multi-agent-syst",
      "name": "Rethinking Query Optimization for Multi-Agent Systems",
      "dir": "rethinking-query-optimization-for-multi-agent-syst/",
