      "score": 0.85,
      "hebbian_credit": 8,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.07993",
      "snippet": "Identifying faithfulness hallucinations in LLM-generated outputs remains challenging. We introduce Hallucination Self-Play (HSP), a novel framework that enables the detector to bootstrap with an evolved generator. HSP involves two roles initialized from the same base model: a detector that assesses faithfulness, and a generator that produces increasingly hard-to-detect hallucinated responses. The evolved generator synthesizes hallucination data to further optimize the detector via rule-based rei"
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.07663",
      "name": "Recursive Self-Improvement in AI: From Bounded Self-Refinement to Autonomous Research Loops",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.07663/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.AI:2607.07663",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.286443+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.286443+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "autonomous-agent",
        "self-reflection",
        "cognitive-architecture"
      ],
      "score": 0.95,
      "hebbian_credit": 10,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.07663",
      "snippet": "AI systems increasingly participate in their own improvement: revising their outputs, adapting their own harnesses during deployment, training on data they generate, and conducting AI research itself. We survey 1,250 arXiv papers (2024-2026) along two axes: what the system improves and the degree of loop closure. The taxonomy separates bounded self-refinement — convergent, evaluable, and already industrial practice — from open-ended recursive self-improvement (RSI), which remains bounded by grou"
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.07858",
      "name": "Agentic AI and Retrieval-Augmented Models in Straight-Through Underwriting (2607.07858)",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.07858/",
