        "multi-agent"
      ],
      "score": 0.75,
      "hebbian_credit": 8,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.07858",
      "snippet": "Artificial intelligence (AI) is beginning to reshape actuarial practice, particularly in domains that require reasoning over unstructured documents, heterogeneous data sources, and regulated decision workflows. Actuaries now face a design space that ranges from traditional rule-based automation to LLMs, RAG, and multi-agent agentic systems that plan, retrieve, call tools, and reflect. This paper examines how these emerging architectures can support actuarial priorities such as transparency, audi"
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.08177",
      "name": "ASMR: Agentic Schema Generation for Ship Maintenance Report Writing (2607.08177)",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.08177/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.MA:2607.08177",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.452454+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.452454+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "multi-agent",
        "autonomous-agent"
      ],
      "score": 0.95,
      "hebbian_credit": 10,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.08177",
      "snippet": "In this paper, we study the automatic schema generation problem: given a collection of historical ship maintenance and operational reports across multiple form categories, automatically discover compact and informative schemas that capture the essential information requirements of each report type. We propose ASMR, a modular agentic framework consisting of two specialized agents: a Field Generation Agent extracts semantic concepts from historical narratives and generates candidate schema fields,"
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.08255",
      "name": "Compete Then Collaborate: Frontier AI Teachers Build a Verifiable Curriculum (2607.08255)",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.08255/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.AI:2607.08255",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.484218+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.484218+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "multi-agent"
      ],
      "score": 0.75,
      "hebbian_credit": 8,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.08255",
      "snippet": "Large language models increasingly serve as teachers generating training data for smaller students. Prior multi-teacher knowledge distillation methods merge outputs without determining which frontier model teaches best, often relying on an LLM judge biased toward its own outputs. We introduce a compete-then-collaborate framework where four frontier AI teachers (Claude, Codex-GPT, Grok, Gemini) are ranked head-to-head by an execution-based judge with fairness controls, and then collaborate to bui"
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.07824",
      "name": "From Triggers to Emotions: A CPM-Grounded Appraisal Multi-Agent for Dynamic Emotional Evolution (2607.07824)",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.07824/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.MA:2607.07824",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.510239+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.510239+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "multi-agent",
        "autonomous-agent"
      ],
      "score": 0.95,
      "hebbian_credit": 10,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.07824",
      "snippet": "LLMs have substantially advanced persona-based dialogue agents for emotion-sensitive role simulation in healthcare, education, counseling, and interactive storytelling. However, two related lines of work leave a key gap: persona-based dialogue systems often encode emotions as static traits or surface-level stylistic cues, and affective dialogue research has largely focused on empathetic response generation toward users rather than modeling the agent persona's own evolving emotional state."
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.08403",
      "name": "Game Theory Driven Multi-Agent Framework Mitigates Language Model Hallucination (2607.08403)",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.08403/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.AI:2607.08403",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.552942+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.552942+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "multi-agent",
        "emergence"
      ],
      "score": 0.95,
      "hebbian_credit": 10,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.08403",
      "snippet": "The application of lightweight LLMs in rule-based scientific domains remains severely limited by their tendency to mimic linguistic patterns rather than reproduce axiomatic reasoning, causing frequent hallucinations. Here, we show that G-Frame, an adaptive multi-agent framework integrating Bayesian and team game principles, establishes an automated closed-loop for high-quality data synthesis and model training. By forcing the internalization of domain constraints through structured reasoning, we"
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.07718",
      "name": "LLT: Local Linear Transformer for PDE Operator Learning (2607.07718)",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.07718/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.LG:2607.07718",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.581899+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.581899+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "long-context"
      ],
      "score": 0.75,
      "hebbian_credit": 8,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.07718",
      "snippet": "Neural operators have become a common approach for learning PDE solution maps and accelerating numerical simulations. Transformer-based neural operators are of particular interest, since attention can learn long-range dependencies in the computational domain. However, standard attention has two major limitations when applied to PDEs: it scales quadratically and lacks an explicit bias toward local interactions."
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.08080",
      "name": "MASTE: A Multi-Agent Pipeline for Zero-Shot Aspect Sentiment Triplet Extraction (2607.08080)",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.08080/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.CL:2607.08080",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.602026+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.602026+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "multi-agent"
      ],
      "score": 0.75,
      "hebbian_credit": 8,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.08080",
      "snippet": "Aspect Sentiment Triplet Extraction (ASTE) requires jointly identifying (aspect, opinion, sentiment) triples from a given review sentence. While LLMs achieve strong zero-shot performance on many NLP benchmarks, their effectiveness on ASTE remains limited, as single-pass generation forces the model to determine span boundaries, opinion grouping, and sentiment polarity in a single decoding step. Common remedies offer only marginal improvements and rely on in-domain demonstrations."
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.08282",
      "name": "Multi-Agent Firewall Architecture for Privacy Protection of Sensitive Data (2607.08282)",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.08282/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.MA:2607.08282",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.618785+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.618785+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "multi-agent"
      ],
      "score": 0.75,
      "hebbian_credit": 8,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.08282",
      "snippet": "While LLMs have become essential productivity tools, their integration into workflows without adequate safeguards creates significant risks. This paper proposes an open-source, privacy-focused, user-facing firewall designed to secure both web-based and programmatic LLM interactions. The architecture combines a browser extension and a proxy for total traffic interception across both HTTP(S) and WebSocket communications."
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.08284",
      "name": "Understanding Axes of Difficulty For Long Context Tasks Via PredicateLongBench (2607.08284)",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.08284/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.AI:2607.08284",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.628910+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.628910+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "long-context"
      ],
      "score": 0.75,
      "hebbian_credit": 8,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.08284",
      "snippet": "Large language models have demonstrated rapidly improving long-context capabilities, prompting a wave of benchmarks designed to evaluate them. However, existing long-context evaluations - from Needle-in-a-Haystack tests to multi-hop reasoning and summarization tasks - predominantly measure average-case performance, and many are either saturated or lack robustness. Notably absent is a systematic way to probe how models perform as we scale up the difficulty of tasks along various axes."
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.08032",
      "name": "What to Keep, What to Forget: A Rate-Distortion View of Memory Compaction in LLMs and Agents (2607.08032)",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.08032/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.LG:2607.08032",
      "status": "digested",
