      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:03.643943+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "memory",
        "autonomous-agent",
        "consciousness"
      ],
      "score": 0.95,
      "hebbian_credit": 10,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.08032",
      "snippet": "LLMs and the agents built on them spend an ever-growing share of their compute and memory on remembering: caching attention keys/values, carrying long prompts, maintaining recurrent state, and storing what happened in previous turns and sessions. Because none of this memory is free, four largely separate research communities have each learned to compact it. They evict or quantize the KV cache, prune or distill prompts, bound architectural state, and consolidate agent memory."
    },
