      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:04.811211+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "sparse-attention",
        "catalyst",
        "long-context"
      ],
      "score": 0.85,
      "hebbian_credit": 8,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.15305",
      "snippet": "Gated Sparse Attention (GSA) incorporates a gated lightning indexer with sigmoid activations, an adaptive sparsity controller, and dual gating at value and output stages. In 1.7B parameter models trained on 400B tokens, GSA matches the efficiency of sparse-only baselines (12-16x speedup at 128K context) while achieving quality gains: perplexity improves from 6.03 to 5.70, RULER scores at 128K nearly double, and attention sinks drop from 47% to under 4%. Loss spikes reduced by 98%."
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2606.30389",
      "name": "PRR: Predict, Reuse, and Repair — Accelerating Dynamic Sparse Attention for Long-Context LLM Decoding",
      "dir": "arxiv-2606.30389/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.LG:2606.30389",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:04.830216+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:04.830216+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "sparse-attention",
        "catalyst",
        "long-context"
      ],
      "score": 0.72,
      "hebbian_credit": 7,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.30389",
      "snippet": "PRR introduces a speculate-reuse-repair runtime that exploits temporal locality in Dynamic Sparse Attention selections. It uses a lightweight EMA-based predictor to predict likely blocks, speculates attention over them while selection is in flight, and incrementally repairs missed blocks using a FlashAttention-based repair kernel. Across long-context benchmarks, PRR reduces per-token decoding latency by up to 40% while preserving downstream task accuracy. This represents a systems-level approach"
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.09713",
      "name": "Closed-Loop Control with Rule-Aligned Small Language Models and Multi-Agent Self-Correction",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.09713/",
      "source": "arXiv:cs.AI:2607.09713",
      "status": "digested",
      "added_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:04.939345+08:00",
      "digested_at": "2026-07-18T12:30:04.939345+08:00",
      "tags": [
        "multi-agent",
        "self-reflection"
      ],
      "score": 0.95,
      "hebbian_credit": 10,
      "layer": "L8",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.09713",
      "snippet": "A key step toward autonomous industrial operation is the ability to create and reconfigure control policies from natural-language requirement specifications, with minimal or no manual redesign. In this setting, policy generation by AI agents can be a credible path when paired with a plant-aware validator."
    },
    {
      "id": "arxiv-2607.10390",
      "name": "A Stepwise Questioning Expert-Editor Multi-Agent Framework for Long-Document Summarization",
      "dir": "arxiv-2607.10390/",
